Fix parameters to execute and logging

Logging should be configurable, or at least the log level. This adds
that. Also we don't need to pass the job to the execute command.

More refactoring to the worker

This adds the marking to process and simplifies the logic of work then
process. We also always use the execute call and handle the timeout
exception separately.

An incomplete but function align worker

This can now align the loops to a motif group. This is basically the
same as the score.py but it has a different command line call.
This is needs to be cleaned up a bit to be finalized but can be tested.
Put job in queue after saving it

Improvements to workers and start of align worker

This refactors some code to make the alignment worker and scoring worker
use a common models method. We also have started some of the work needed
to create a worker for alignments.

Add a worker that will score input against motifs

This is the first of 2 workers we need to add that use the queue. This
worker will pull data from the beanstalk queue and then create a java
job to process the data. At the moment this does not correctly update
the database if the jar takes too long. It replaces the old perl based
queue in queue/.

First attempt at new beanstalk based queue

This begins the process of adding a beanstalk queue to the webserver.
The current queue is based on perl and is causing issues with running
too long and taking up too much memory. I'm not sure why this is
happening.

I add 2 workers, one for the scoring of an input (bin/score.py) and one
for the aligning of a loop to a model (bin/align.py). These are based
off the generic worker class in JAR3Doutput/worker.py which is a
modification of the worker class from r3d-2-msa. I'm planning on using
subprocess32 as this improves the subprocess in python 2.6 (our current
version). It notably adds timeout support, something we need. The code
is untested right now but this is an outline of what I will attempt to
write.

Once this is done we will remove the queue/ directory entirely.
